Introduction: Exercises for Week 1-3

In this lab you will put in practice the content we discussed in weeks 1-3 of MILD. You will take a look at time series data, evaluate and interpret descriptive statistics and plot for these data, and estimate N=1 time series models. Specifically you will fit AR(1) and AR(2) models, an AR(1) model with a covariate, and a VAR(1) model. We include different estimation techniques for these models, including both frequentist and Bayesian techniques. The Bayesian techniques will be helpful to provide you with a basis for once we move on to more complicated models and analyses in later weeks.

The data we will work with

In this lab you will mainly work with real data from Schuurman, Houtveen and Hamaker (2015, Frontiers). These are daily diary measurements from two women, whom we refer to as Jane and Mary (not their real names). Both womens data consist of about 100 consecutive days of repeated measurements, some days the scores are missing because they did not answer. The original data contains various measures on mood, positive and negative affect, and symptoms surrounding the womens periods.

Installing and loading packages

Some of the exercises in this lab make use of r-packages or other software you need to run via R.

Specifically youll need these r-packages: foreign, for loading an SPSS data file; psych, for loading an SPSS data file; rjags, for fitting the Bayesian models; coda, for running summary stats and plots on the Bayesian analysis results.

And youll need this additional piece of software (outside of R): JAGS, because rjags depends on this program. JAGS is software for fitting Bayesian models, and you will use it via r with package rjags.

2. Introduction to time series analysis for single cases (n=1) and single variables

In the following we will try out fitting time series models to mood time series for Jane and Mary (separately). We will start by using different estimation methods common in classical statistics. Later on, well try Bayesian models.

2.1 AR models using least squares estimation

The simplest way to fit a N=1 autoregressive model is estimating it as a linear regression model using least squares with the lm() function. In order to do this, we need to first create the lagged predictor variables that can be used to predict y(t).

Well stick to fitting an AR(1) model with this technique (although you could try out an AR model with more lags!). Below is code to create the lagged variable we need as our predictor variable, namely our original variable shifted one point in time. We first make a function to lag variables, which is then applied to the data of Jane.

lagmatrix <- function(x,max.lag) 
  embed(c(rep(NA,max.lag), x), max.lag+1)

y1L_Jane <- lagmatrix(dat_Jane,1)[,2]

Moreover, we can now regress y(t) on y(t-1) using least squares in lm() and hence fit the AR(1) model:

ar1_in_lm<-lm(dat_Jane~y1L_Jane)

2.2 Autoregressive modeling using function arima

We can easily fit N=1 time series models with package arima which is native in R (i.e., it does not need to be installed or loaded). ARIMA uses a state space modeling framework which combines maximum likelihood estimation and the kalman filter to fit time series models. As a result, it will handle missing data more elegantly than the approach based on lm() and least squares, which simply deletes all cases that have missings on either the outcome y(t) or the predictor y(t-1). Use ?arima in R to learn more and check out the default options.

Fitting an AR(1) model with arima

You can fit an AR(1) model to the data of Jane using:

arima(dat_Jane, c(1,0,0))
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = dat_Jane, order = c(1, 0, 0))
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1  intercept
##       0.0752    74.8807
## s.e.  0.1321     1.6063
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 170.5:  log likelihood = -303.15,  aic = 612.29

The three numbers in c(1,0,0) signify in order:

  • the number of lags you want in terms autoregressive coefficients (the ar part of arima models) for your time series model. Here we have indicated we want a lag 1 autoregressive effect and nothing more.

  • the level of integration you want for your time series model (the i part of arima models), which is not currently covered in this course, and pertains to specific types of non-stationarity. We have put it to zero, because we do not want an integrated model here, but a simple AR(1) model.

  • the number of moving average terms you want, that is, the number of lags you want in terms of movering average effects. We have put it to zero, because we do not want moving average effects here.

3. Delving deeper into autoregressive modeling

For the following exercises, we turn to Bayesian analysis using JAGS (software outside of R), via package rjags. Or if you like, you can now switch to our lab in Mplus for week 1-3, which is also based on Bayesian techniques.

An advantage of using Bayesian analyses is that we can easily extend models to incorporate covariates, multivariate outcomes, latent variables, or multiple subjects. In these exercises however, well still stick to relatively simple, single case, autoregressive models for single variables.

In that context, we have as an advantage that instead of specifying the AR(1) model in one equation with an intercept, we can specify it in two equations, in which the first is used to center the data (by subtracting the mean from each observed score), and the second equation is used to specify the AR(1) model on the centered data. Note we are not using the samlpe mean to center the data, but we estimate this mean as part of the model: We use latent centering (a best practice for centering).

If you are not familiar with Bayesian analyses and/or JAGS, it is a good idea to first read our informal intro to Bayesian analysis.

3.1 The Bayesian AR(1) model

The autoregressive model we fill fit here has three parameters that well estimate: the mean, the autoregressive parameter, and the variance of the residuals (i.e., the innovation variance). That is, we estimate the same number of parameters as before, but rather than an intercept, we directly estimate the mean.

3.1.a Specifying the model

This is the JAGS code for the model (everything in between parentheses), which we will supply to JAGS for the analysis (it is provided as a text file with the lab files, make sure it is in your working directory). Take a look at the model specification, including the priors that were specified. The priors specified are intended to be uninformative (i.e., flat and wide).

cat("model{
   

#####likelihood or data model######
    for (t in 2:nt) 
    ## model for timepoint 2 onwards
    {
        y[t]~dnorm(muy[t],Ipre) ## Ipre is the innovation precision
        z[t] <- y[t] - mu ## z[t] are centered scores 
        muy[t]<- mu + phi*z[t-1] ## mu is mean, phi is autoregressive parameter
    }

####timepoint 1#######
 ## defining things needed for time point one.
    z[1] <- y[1]-mu  
    
####priors###########
    Ipre <- inverse(Ivar) ## innovation precision
    Ivar ~dunif(0,300)   ##innovation variance
    phi~dunif(-1,1) ## autoregression coefficient
    mu~dnorm(50,.001) ## mean
}

")
## model{
##    
## 
## #####likelihood or data model######
##  for (t in 2:nt) 
##  ## model for timepoint 2 onwards
##  {
##      y[t]~dnorm(muy[t],Ipre) ## Ipre is the innovation precision
##      z[t] <- y[t] - mu ## z[t] are centered scores 
##      muy[t]<- mu + phi*z[t-1] ## mu is mean, phi is autoregressive parameter
##  }
## 
## ####timepoint 1#######
##  ## defining things needed for time point one.
##  z[1] <- y[1]-mu  
##  
## ####priors###########
##     Ipre <- inverse(Ivar) ## innovation precision
##     Ivar ~dunif(0,300)   ##innovation variance
##     phi~dunif(-1,1) ## autoregression coefficient
##     mu~dnorm(50,.001) ## mean
## }

  • If you are not familiar with Bayesian analyses and/or JAGS, it is a good idea to first read our informal intro to Bayesian analysis available on the Ulearning platform.

  • What do you think of our prior specifications, given what you know of the measurement scale we are using for mood?

We will fit the model in JAGS via package rjags with three chains. For each chain, initial values for each parameter can be specified in lists as follows:

ins = list(list(phi=.6, Ivar=100, mu=50),
           list(phi=.3, Ivar=60, mu=60),
           list(phi=-.2, Ivar=80, mu=70))

It is also possible to not specify any starting values, in which case they will be generated by JAGS based on the specified priors.

We also need to specify the length of the time series nt and provide it to JAGS as data, because this quantity is used in the model code in the for loop. We specify this as follows (and well add this to the data for JAGS later):

nt=length(dat_Jane)

Now we have everything needed to run the model. We use the function jags.model() to compile the model for JAGS. This requires us to specify:

  1. the model file (given above)

  2. data to be used with the model file (for Jane), including nt

  3. initial values if we want to provide them

  4. the number of chains we want to use

jags_AR1 <- jags.model('AR1model.txt',
                       data = list('nt' = nt, 
                                   'y' = as.numeric(dat_Jane)),
                       inits = ins,
                       n.chains = 3) 
## Compiling model graph
##    Resolving undeclared variables
##    Allocating nodes
## Graph information:
##    Observed stochastic nodes: 75
##    Unobserved stochastic nodes: 18
##    Total graph size: 183
## 
## Initializing model

3.1.b Running the model

Now we have specified our JAGS model, we can get Bayesian samples from it. We first do 1000 samples (i.e., iterations) for burn-in purposes for each chain.

update(jags_AR1, 1000)

Next, we ask for 2000 additional samples per chain on which we will base our results. We save the samples and obtain the results for parameters phi, mu, and Ivar (autoregressive coefficient, mean, and innovation variance):

samps_AR1 <- coda.samples(model = jags_AR1, 
                          variable.names = c('phi','mu','Ivar'),
                          n.iter = 2000)

Now are results (which are in samps_AR1) are based on 3 chains of 2000 iterations each (while we used 3000 iterations as burn-in for each chain).

3.1.c Checking convergence

Now we have to do some convergence checks. Specifically, we check

  1. trace plots, which should look like fat caterpillars, with good overlap (mixing) of the different chains (represented by different colors)

  2. the Gelman-Rubin statistics (plots and summary stats), which should be very close to 1 (smaller than 1.05)

  3. the density plots, which should look smooth and unimodal

plot(samps_AR1,density=FALSE)

gelman.diag(samps_AR1) 
## Potential scale reduction factors:
## 
##      Point est. Upper C.I.
## Ivar          1       1.00
## mu            1       1.00
## phi           1       1.01
## 
## Multivariate psrf
## 
## 1
plot(samps_AR1,trace=FALSE)

The density plots are nice and smooth, trace plots look like fat caterpillars, gelman-rubin statistics are good. Convergence seems in order.

###3.2 Bayesian AR(2) analysis Next, we will fit the AR(2) model for Jane and Mary. In this model, we regress the y(t) not only on y(t-1), but also on y(t-2); hence, both yesterday and the day before yesterday serve as predictors for today.

This model has 4 parameters: the mean of the variables, the two autoregressive parameters, and the variance of the residuals.

3.2a Specifying the model

An AR(2) model can be specified using (this is provided in a text file with the lab exercises, store it in your working directory):

cat("model{
   

#####model######
    for (t in 3:nt)  
    ### model for timepoint 3 onwards
    {
        y[t] ~ dnorm(muy[t],Ipre) ## Ipre is innovation precision
        z[t] <- y[t]-mu #centered scores
        muy[t] <- mu + phi1*z[t-1] + phi2*z[t-2] ## mu is mean, phi1 and phi2 are the autregressive parameters
                
        
    }

####timepoint 1 and 2 #######

    z[1] <- y[1] - mu ### model for time point one
    z[2] <- y[2] - mu ### model for time point two
    
            
####priors###########
       
    Ipre <- inverse(Ivar) ## innovation precision as function of the variance
    Ivar ~ dunif(0,300)   ##prior for innovation variance

    phi1 ~ dunif(-1,1) ## prior for lag 1 autoregression coefficient
      phi2 ~ dunif(-1,1) ## prior for lag 2 autoregression coefficient
    mu ~ dnorm(50,.001) ## prior for the mean
        
              

}

")

##    
## 
## #####model######

##  {

##      muy[t] <- mu + phi1*z[t-1] + phi2*z[t-2] ## mu is mean, phi1 and phi2 are the autregressive parameters
##

and we compile the model:

3.3 A Bayesian AR(1) model with a covariate

Next, we add an exogenous covariate (i.e., a variable that is purely a predictor variable) to the AR(1) model. We have information on when each women had her period (score 1) or not (score 0). For this variable, we have filled in scores where there were missing observations, because exogenous variables are not allowed to have missing observations in the analysis. Given the nature of the variable, we could surmise how to complete these observations (if a woman had her period before and after the missing observation, we indicate this missing observation as a period day).

An alternative way to deal with missings in covariates is to specify a likelihood/data model for the covariate as well, next to the dependent variable, or to impute for these observations in another way. This is beyond the scope of this course, however.

3.3a Check out the data.

Load the data for Mary and Jane, and explore their data with (for instance) a time series plot:

dat_predJane = read.table("Ar1pred_Jane.dat", header=TRUE, na.strings="*")
dat_predMary = read.table("Ar1pred_Mary.dat", header=TRUE, na.strings="*")

3.3b Fit the model, and interpret the results.

Take a look at the JAGS model code for the AR(1) model with an exogenous predictor (see below, or look in the file AR1predmodel.txt - make sure this file is in your working directory). Note that in this model specification, we are estimating an intercept (int) rather than a mean (mu) for mood.

Note that we are estimating a concurrent effect of the variable period on mood.

cat("model{
   

#####model######
    for (t in 2:nt) 
    ###model for timepoint 2 onwards
    {
        y[t] ~ dnorm(muy[t],Ipre)  
        ## Ipre is innovation precision
        muy[t] <- int + phi*y[t-1] + b1*x[t] 
        ## int is the intercept, phi is autoregressive parameters
    }

    #####priors###########
       
    Ipre <- inverse(Ivar) ## innovation precision
    Ivar ~ dunif(0,500)   ## innovation variance

    phi~dunif(-1,1) ## autoregression coefficient
      b1~dnorm(0,.001) ## exogenous effect
      b2~dnorm(0,.001) ## exogenous effect (lagged)
    int~dnorm(50,.001) ## intercept
        
              

}
")

##

4 Vector or multivariate autoregressive modeling

In the following, well practice with fitting multivariate autoregressive models: VAR models.

4.1 VAR(1) analysis

As a final model we fit a first-order vector autoregressive model for two variables: A bivariate VAR(1) model. The two variables we will model are mood and nervous tension.

  • What kind of effects would you expect nervous tension and mood to have on each other over time? What about concurrently?

4.1a Check out the data.

Start by loading the data for both women, and make time series plots:

  • Judging from looking at the data, do the two variables seem to sync up over time within each woman?

Check out the model code.

Now, take a look at the JAGS model code for the bivariate VAR(1) model (also in VAR1model.txt, make sure this file is in your working directory.

cat("model{
   

#####model######
    for (t in 2:nt) 
    
    ###likelihood or data model for timepoint 2 onwards
    {
        y[t,1:2]~dmnorm(muy[t,1:2],Ipre[1:2,1:2])
        
        #latent centered variables
        z[t,1] <- y[t,1] - mu1  
        z[t,2] <- y[t,2] - mu2
        
        # autoregressive equations
        muy[t,1]<- mu1 + phi11*z[t-1,1] + phi12*z[t-1,2] 
        muy[t,2]<- mu2 + phi22*z[t-1,2] + phi21*z[t-1,1] 
        
        #note: mu1 and mu2 are the means for each variable
        # phi11 and phi22 are the autoregressive coefficients for each variable
        # phi 12 and phi21 are the cross-lagged coefficients for each variable
    }

####timepoint 1#######

    z[1,1] <- y[1,1]-mu1 ### centered score for time point 1 for variable 1.
  z[1,2] <- y[1,2]-mu2 ### centered score for time point 1 for variable 2.
    
            
####priors###########
  
  
###Innovatian variance-covariance matrix, and/or precision matrix 
  
### prior specifications for means and regression coefficients ###
  
  mu1~dnorm(50,.001) ## mean
  mu2~dnorm(3,.001) ## mean

  phi11~dnorm(0,.001) ## autoregression coefficient
    phi12~dnorm(0,.001) ## cross-lagged coefficient
    phi21~dnorm(0,.001) ## cross-lagged coefficient
    phi22~dnorm(0,.001) ## autoregression coefficient
    
### prior specifications for the covariance matrix of the innovations ###
  
  ## priors for the two variances:
  Ivar1 ~ dunif(0,300) ## innovation variance y1
    Ivar2 ~ dunif(0,300) ## innovation variance y2
    
    ##prior for the correlation among the innovations:
    Icor ~ dunif(-1,1) ## innovation correlation
    ## turning correlation into a covariance:
    Icov <- Icor*sqrt(Ivar1)*sqrt(Ivar2) 
    
    ##Sticking all of the above into one covariance matrix:
    Ivar[1,1] <- Ivar1
  Ivar[2,2] <- Ivar2
  Ivar[2,1] <- Icov
  Ivar[1,2] <- Icov
  
    ## Turning the covariance matrix into a precision matrix:
  Ipre <- inverse(Ivar)

}
")
## model{
##    
## 
## #####model######
##  for (t in 2:nt) 
##  
##  ###likelihood or data model for timepoint 2 onwards
